```tsx
import { TypeWriter } from "@ui-universe/ui";

export default function Example() {
  return (
    <div className="p-8 bg-gray-900 text-green-400 font-mono">
      <div className="mb-6">
        <h1 className="text-2xl mb-4">Terminal Session</h1>
        <TypeWriter
          text="$ sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y"
          speed={80}
          cursor={true}
          cursorChar="_"
          className="text-lg"
        />
      </div>

      <div className="mb-6">
        <TypeWriter
          text="Installing packages... [████████████████████] 100% Complete"
          speed={25}
          cursor={false}
          cursorChar=""
          className="text-yellow-300"
          delay={2000}
        />
      </div>

      <div>
        <TypeWriter
          text="System ready. Welcome to the matrix."
          speed={120}
          cursor={true}
          cursorChar="█"
          className="text-cyan-300 text-xl font-bold"
          delay={4000}
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

This example creates a terminal-style interface with three TypeWriter components, each using different customizations:

1. **First TypeWriter**: Uses `speed={80}` (slower than default 50ms), keeps `cursor={true}`, and uses `cursorChar="_"` (underscore instead of default "|")

2. **Second TypeWriter**: Uses `speed={25}` (faster), `cursor={false}` to hide the cursor completely, and shows a progress bar-style message

3. **Third TypeWriter**: Uses `speed={120}` (much slower for dramatic effect), `cursor={true}`, and `cursorChar="█"` (solid block character) for a retro computer feel

The component creates a cohesive terminal/matrix theme with staggered delays to simulate a real command-line session.

